\section{Introduction}

\subsection{Motivation}

Machine learning practitioners often run dozens or hundreds of experiments with different hyperparameters, model architectures, and training configurations. Manually reviewing each experiment to identify the best performing configuration is time-consuming and error-prone.

This project presents an \textbf{RL (Reinforcement Learning) benchmark} where AI agents learn to automate the process of triaging ML experiment results. The environment simulates real-world scenarios where data scientists must:

\begin{itemize}
	\item \textbf{Identify the best performing experiment} from multiple runs
	\item \textbf{Detect overfitting} - experiments that memorize training data but fail on validation
	\item \textbf{Suggest next experiments} - recommend promising hyperparameter configurations
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Contributions}

Our main contributions are:

\begin{enumerate}
	\item An \textbf{OpenEnv-compliant} environment following the official Meta-PyTorch specification
	\item Three tasks with \textbf{increasing difficulty} testing different ML analysis skills
	\item A \textbf{stateless HTTP architecture} with state serialization for scalable deployment
	\item A \textbf{built-in web interface} deployed on Hugging Face Spaces
	\item An \textbf{inference pipeline} demonstrating how AI agents interact with the environment
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Project Links}

\begin{itemize}
	\item \textbf{Hugging Face Space}: \url{https://huggingface.co/spaces/charansaiponnada/ml-experiment-triage-env}
	\item \textbf{GitHub Repository}: \url{https://github.com/charansaiponnada/ml-experiment-triage-env}
\end{itemize}

\newpage

\section{Background and Related Work}

\subsection{Reinforcement Learning Environments}

Reinforcement learning environments are standardized interfaces that allow AI agents to interact with simulated tasks. The OpenEnv framework, developed by Meta-PyTorch, provides a standardized way to build and deploy these environments.

Popular RL benchmarks include:
\begin{itemize}
	\item \textbf{Atari Games} - Arcade gameplay
	\item \textbf{MuJoCo} - Physics simulation
	\item \textbf{OpenAI Gym} - Classic control tasks
	\item \textbf{StarCraft II} - Complex strategy
\end{itemize}

Our environment focuses on a novel domain: \textbf{ML experiment triage}, combining elements of information retrieval, anomaly detection, and recommendation systems.

\subsection{OpenEnv Framework}

OpenEnv provides:
\begin{itemize}
	\item Standardized \texttt{Action}, \texttt{Observation}, and \texttt{State} base classes
	\item HTTP and WebSocket API endpoints
	\item Automatic web interface generation
	\item Docker deployment support
	\item Integration with Hugging Face Spaces
\end{itemize}

Our implementation follows the official OpenEnv specification, ensuring compatibility with the broader ecosystem.

\subsection{MLOps and Experiment Tracking}

Modern ML workflows involve:
\begin{itemize}
	\item \textbf{Experiment tracking} (MLflow, Weights \& Biases, TensorBoard)
	\item \textbf{Hyperparameter optimization} (Optuna, Ray Tune)
	\item \textbf{Model selection} and comparison
	\item \textbf{Overfitting detection} via training curves
\end{itemize}

Our environment abstracts these concepts into a gamified RL task, making it ideal for training and evaluating AI assistants for MLOps tasks.

