		.4 Dockerfile.
	}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Data Flow}

The ML Experiment Triage environment uses a client-server architecture where the client (inference script) interacts with the server (FastAPI) through HTTP endpoints.

\begin{figure}[h]
	\centering
	\begin{tikzpicture}[
			node distance=1.5cm,
			block/.style={rectangle, draw, rounded corners, minimum width=2.5cm, minimum height=1cm, align=center},
			arrow/.style={thick,->,>=stealth}
		]

		\node[block, fill=blue!20] (client) at (0,0) {Client\\inference.py};
		\node[block, fill=green!20] (api) at (5,0) {OpenEnv Server\\FastAPI};
		\node[block, fill=yellow!20] (env) at (10,0) {MLTriage\\Environment};

		\draw[arrow] (client) -- node[above] {HTTP Request} (api);
		\draw[arrow] (api) -- node[above] {Create New Instance} (env);
		\draw[arrow] (env) -- node[above] {Response} (api);
		\draw[arrow] (api) -- node[above] {JSON Response} (client);

		\node[block, fill=purple!20, minimum width=3cm] (llm) at (0,-2.5) {GPT-4o-mini\\LLM};

		\draw[arrow] (client) -- node[right] {Prompts} (llm);
		\draw[arrow] (llm) -- node[right] {Action JSON} (client);

	\end{tikzpicture}
\end{figure}

The key innovation is \textbf{state serialization} - since HTTP creates a new environment for each request, we serialize the entire game state into the observation and pass it back with each action.

\newpage

\section{Data Models}

\subsection{Experiment Record}

Each experiment is represented as a structured record:

\begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, style=mystyle]
class ExperimentRecord(BaseModel):
    exp_id: str           # Unique identifier
    model_name: str      # e.g., resnet18, resnet50
    learning_rate: float # Learning rate
    epochs: int          # Training epochs
    train_acc: float    # Training accuracy
    val_acc: float      # Validation accuracy
    train_loss: float   # Training loss
    val_loss: float     # Validation loss
    notes: str          # Additional notes
    status: str          # pending, investigated, discarded
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{Action Space}

The agent can perform four types of actions:

\begin{table}[h]
	\centering
	\begin{tabular}{@{}llp{6cm}c@{}}
		\toprule
		Action               & Parameters          & Description                & Reward       \\
		\midrule
		\texttt{investigate} & \texttt{exp\_id}    & Examine experiment details & +0.1         \\
		\texttt{discard}     & \texttt{exp\_id}    & Mark as dead end           & +0.15 / -0.1 \\
		\texttt{suggest}     & \texttt{suggestion} & Propose next config        & 0.0 - 0.5    \\
		\texttt{summarize}   & \texttt{summary}    & Final answer               & 0.0 - 1.0    \\
		\bottomrule
	\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsection{Observation Space}

The environment returns:

\begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, style=mystyle]
class MLTriageObservation(Observation):
    experiments: List[ExperimentRecord]  # All experiments
    current_step: int                     # Current step number
    max_steps: int                        # Maximum steps allowed
    task_id: int                          # Current task ID
    task_description: str                 # Task instructions
    feedback: str                        # Feedback from last action
    serialized_state: Dict               # Full game state
\end{lstlisting}

\newpage

\section{Tasks and Rewards}

\subsection{Task 1: Find Best Experiment (Easy)}

\textbf{Goal:} Identify the best performing experiment from 8 options.

\textbf{Data:} 8 experiments with varying configurations

\textbf{Ground Truth:} \texttt{exp\_004} has the highest validation accuracy (0.94)

\textbf{Reward Structure:}
\begin{itemize}
	\item Investigate any experiment: +0.1
	\item Summarize correct (exp\_004): +1.0
	\item Summarize incorrect: +0.0
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Max Steps:} 10

\subsection{Task 2: Identify Overfitting (Medium)}

\textbf{Goal:} Find and discard all overfitting experiments.

\textbf{Definition:} An experiment is overfitting if:
\[
	\text{train\_acc} > 0.97 \text{ AND } \text{val\_acc} < 0.75
\]

\textbf{Ground Truth:} exp\_002, exp\_006, exp\_009

\textbf{Reward Structure:}
\begin{itemize}
	\item Correctly discard overfitting: +0.15 each
	\item Incorrectly discard good experiment: -0.1
	\item Investigate experiment: +0.1
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Max Steps:} 15

\subsection{Task 3: Suggest Next Configuration (Hard)}

\textbf{Goal:} Analyze patterns and suggest the next hyperparameter configuration.

\textbf{Ground Truth:}
\begin{itemize}
	\item \texttt{learning\_rate}: 0.001
	\item \texttt{epochs}: 50
	\item \texttt{model\_name}: resnet50
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Reward Structure:}
\begin{itemize}
	\item 3 fields match: +0.5
	\item 2 fields match: +0.35
	\item 1 field match: +0.15
	\item No match: +0.0
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Max Steps:} 20

\subsection{Overall Reward System}

The reward system is designed to provide dense feedback for each action, encouraging the agent to learn effective triage strategies.

\begin{figure}[h]
	\centering
	\begin{tikzpicture}[
			node distance=1.2cm,
			task/.style={rectangle, draw, rounded corners, minimum width=3cm, minimum height=2cm, align=center},
