\section{Evaluation}

\subsection{Baseline Scores}

Using GPT-4o-mini as the agent:

\begin{table}[h]
	\centering
	\begin{tabular}{@{}lcc@{}}
		\toprule
		Task                 & Difficulty & Baseline Score \\
		\midrule
		Find Best Experiment & Easy       & 0.85           \\
		Identify Overfitting & Medium     & 0.62           \\
		Suggest Next Config  & Hard       & 0.41           \\
		\bottomrule
	\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsection{Metrics}

\begin{itemize}
	\item \textbf{Total Reward}: Sum of all step rewards
	\item \textbf{Episode Length}: Number of steps taken
	\item \textbf{Success Rate}: Episodes with reward > 0.5
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Reproducibility}

The environment is deterministic given the same task ID and action sequence. All experiment data is hardcoded in \texttt{ml\_triage\_environment.py}.

\newpage

\section{Conclusion}

We presented an OpenEnv-compliant RL benchmark for ML experiment triage. The environment:

\begin{itemize}
	\item Provides three tasks with increasing difficulty
	\item Uses a stateless HTTP architecture with state serialization
	\item Deploys automatically to Hugging Face Spaces
	\item Includes a web interface for manual interaction
	\item Demonstrates an inference pipeline for AI agents
\end{itemize}

Future work includes:
\begin{itemize}
	\item Adding more tasks (e.g., error analysis, hyperparameter sensitivity)
	\item Supporting dynamic experiment data
	\item Integrating with real ML tracking tools
	\item Training specialized agents using RL
\end{itemize}

